< Review>
Brought my phone here, to have the screen fixed. After having God awful service here the first day, they repaired the screen. The next day I noticed, there were a million bubbles under the screen. Took the phone back 4 times, because the guy at the register kept assuring me they were waiting on a new machine. Two weeks later, while typing, my phone screen cracks again, and Im beyond pissed. The material used to replace the screen was beyond cheap. When I returned for them to repair the millions of bubbles, and the new crack, I was told they were going to try and repair the bubbles, but they cannot warranty their cheap glass replacement. When I asked why, he said they don't warranty the glass, even though it was obvious it was done poorly. I was initially going to leave my phone to fix the millions of bubbles, but he said the crack in the glass would get worse. I cannot fathom why the hell i would leave my phone, so it could be in worse condition when I get it returned to me. I referred my cousin here, because of their cheap prices, but she too has millions of bubbles under her screen. STAY CLEAR OF THIS PLACE!

********Update*********

Reluctantly, I went back here, at a friends request - this time things were better. They fixed my phone in the time frame they promised, so no complaints out of me this time. So, I had an awful experience, and a much better experience, hence the 3 stars.</Review>

< Review>
It really helps when an employee actually knows a store policy.  Sign on the door "Only two parties allowed in the store at one time".  We look in the store, one party of two people, we make the second party and walk in (we are not within 15 feet of anyone in the store and are wearing our masks)... lady behind the counter, You have to wait outside.  Ok, questioning the sign...  "Your sign says two parties, not two people."  Atempting to get a legitimate clarification.  Rudely, she responds...  "You have to wait outside, that is our store policy, if you do not like it, we do not need your business."   She was right, they did not need my business and we went to Doc Bernsteins (one block away).  I do not care if your policy is Two people in the store at one time, if that is what you want, that is fine...  but your sign should say that, not " Two parties", which many people will take to interpret as two groups of people together.  Simple fix, update your store sign to say "Two People".< /Review>

Take your time and try all the different flavors and dairy-free sorbets. The staffis so nice and patient that they will let you try them all before choosing. Although a scoop is five bucks, the flavors are unique and impactful. It seems they draw inspiration from a variety of culinary backgrounds and they do a good job of representing those flavors. Definitely worth a try.<//Review>

< gmap_id>
0x80ecf11f1d545261:0x8d49b53ff457748b<//gmap_id>
<Pictures>None< /Pictures>< review>
Local review by a local:  Excellent locally made ice-cream that has great creative flavors.  They are doing a great job of being COVID-19 safe, and you order via a window in the door.  The only downsides are samples are not available so you could be stuck with something too sweet for example.  Since I am older, I tend to go with robust flavors with things like pie crust in them.  While I thought the Boysenberry was totally amazing in flavor and reminded me of the long defunct Ben & Jerry's version for decades ago, I could do without pie pieces. In keeping with simplicity, I also had a scoop of Vanilla Bean.  It was refreshing.  While they did have a single flavored Strawberry & a Complex Chocolate, I kind of missed a Coffee or a Pistachio.  There was an intriguing Lemon combo, but without sampling why risk it.  While I see the appeal for the Millennial crowd, us mature folk do enjoy the classics, so please make more of those.  IN any case, it made an excellent dessert after a big meal at Ox & Anchor around the block.  This local ice-cream was also available at the Avila Barn, where sundaes where available.  I am not sure if that is possible in the future here....I guess it depends upon this new C-19 age.  Regardless of the above, it is simply marvelous to see this wonderful venture surviving in downtown SLO, despite the many challenges. Thank you so much for all your hard work!</review>

<user>116976417488826345286< /user><Name>Max Goldberg< /Name><Date>1564871249832< /Date><Rate>5</Rate><review>So you know when people all tell you an ice cream place is amazing, and you get excited when you go, then as you're getting your first samples you worry if it's all hype? You've had some pretty amazing ice cream before. That first taste had better be pretty spectacular, right? So even if it's some of the best ice cream you've ever had, it's not going to blow you away, and if it's in any way mediocre, you'll be flat out disappointed. That's the headspace I was in as I was handed my first taste of McConnell's ice cream on a metal spoon. I took a bite and I suddenly had my perspective on the entire concept of ice cream shifted, because it is some of the best ice cream in some of the most insightful flavors you'll ever see. Every flavor is delicious, good luck picking one.

You want to know what kind of wizards these guys are? They made cornbread into an ice cream. And it's genuinely the best ice cream my wife and I have ever had. It's so good we're getting extra to go.

My only constructive criticism is that the waffle cone is not great. It tastes just like a regular cone. But with ice cream this good you won't care. They could charge 150% as much and it would still be worth it.< /review><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Response>

<user_id>110245839572161700410<//user_id><user_name>Alexis Marsh<//user_name><Date>1525763996014<//Date><rate>5< /rate><Text>Highly recommend the Hemet Post Office for PASSPORTS! I know there is walk-in & appointments you can arrange. The passport agent you want to meet with is Claudia. She speaks both English & Spanish fluently. Some info you may find useful is to

1. Have your application filled out in advance with black ink only!
2. Have photo copies of your ID (front & back), & present your original birth certificate along with a copy of your birth certificate.
3. You can get a passport photo here! $15
4. The application process is 10-15 minutes top! (She's fast!)
5. You can get your money order with the passport agent with debit or cash.
6. If you have a renewal or recall having a passport years ago, you have to turn them in with your application.

I suggest walking in person to clarify any questions or even to make an appointment! She's there full-time for passport services only. Also there's a Facebook page with helpful info about the passport applications/prices if you search under "Hemet USPS Passports"

The passport agent does have weekly rotating days off so that‚Äôs why it‚Äôs helpful to schedule an appointment in advance.

The passport hours of operation are Monday-Friday from 9:30am-12:30pm & Saturday appointments only from 6am-9:45am & then walk-ins from 10:00am-12:30pm.

<Review>Stay away from this dental office and the South Gate location too (Garden Dental)

I cannot say nothing negative about the doctor's because they do their job. The problem is the billing department. Be careful with Nancy!! she is the words.

I don't know if she gets pay commission or what but is hard to trust and deal with an office where the billing department don't know what is doing.

A good collection department is an asset to every business, and asset that can turn into a liability when there is an overzealous and do-it-all collector.

This is the case at Downey Family Cosmetic Dentistry and Garden Dental , his collector also takes care of customer service, interferes with the doctor's decisions and tries to run the office as she wants disregarding patients rights and already signed contracts.

Bill collection being as important as it is for a business should be set aside of customer service, in this office the person in charge of collections interferes in every aspect of the medical treatment including overriding the doctor's orders. She should be emphasize on the payment of accounts instead of poking her nose on items unrelated to her duties.

Please remember how easy liability can extend from one place to the other, also I'm the paying customer and expect to be treated with honesty and respect, I'm not getting NOTHING for free from your dental office and expect to be treated respectfully and that your office shows the professionalism the State of California entrusts you.< /Review>< user_name>

<user_id>104198978486067335231<//user_id>< user_name>
Cryschelle Jeffery< /user_name>
<date>1554847806618<//date>< rate>
5</rate>
< Review>
Sandwiched between two neighborhoods and right off of Thousand Oaks Blvd, this is a large park popular for soccer games, parties, jogging, and dog walking. There is a basketball court, a covered patio area, a playground, horseshoe court, and a large grassy field. Bathrooms are unisex and lock after dark. There's parking all around the park but its shared with the nearby condos and mechanics.
The playground has been renovated in the last few years and is very nice. There are also a number of majestic, tall oak trees that shade much of the park.<//Review>

<date>1567041445690< /date><Rating>4</Rating>< review>
Very clean park with water fountains, bathrooms, swings for both infants and older children. It has a mixture of soft asphalt, sand and wood chips in the play areas. Large park with baseball backdrop and basketball court near by. Also a walking trail around the edge</review>

< review>
My wife and some friends did the full tasting menu here.  One of us was also Celiac, so it was nice that they adjusted her menu to be Gluten Free and still got her most of what we had.  The service was great, the wait staff was super attentive and welcoming.  The outdoor seating was really well done and felt very comfortable.  I don't drink wine, but I'm told that the wine pairing was actually great.  We did add a couple extra Black Truffle dishes and the stand out ended up being a Black Truffle spaghetti.  The other items were all very good.  I think it's a great spot if you want a tasting menu, perhaps not the best, but certainly worthy of their Michelin Star.</review>

<userid>110830390221669638642</userid><username>Christine Mamuad<//username><Date>1614725530709</Date><Rate>2<//Rate><text>Came here for our anniversary dinner, and although the service was wonderful and flawless, the tasting menu was just... good. It falls short compared to other Michelin star restaurants in the vicinity of SF, especially when taking the exorbitant price into account.

We ordered the wine pairing to go with each dish and struggled to perceive how any of the wines enhanced the food, or vice versa. The person who poured the wines added nothing beyond what was already printed on the menu.

Two of the courses were tasty, interesting, but not particularly daring takes on existing dishes (scallop ceviche, and fish and chips). One dish was outstanding in its creativity and flavor (a ravioli-type pasta). The lamb rack was good, but one could find something comparable at a decent steakhouse for a better price. The vegetable ragout meant to be a side for the lamb was oversalted and inedible, souring the meal, though the staff reacted swiftly and admirably to replace it.

Dessert was good, though not exactly noteworthy, with our choices of a citrus ricotta crepe and a chocolate concorde cake.

I commend the staff for delivering excellent service, but for the price, the food needed to be at that same level of excellence. Overall, this was a disappointment, a contrast with every other wonderful meal we had in Napa at a fraction of the cost.<//text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOTcrpCP0bajqoSkvZyuUUTw2gwf7IoZsIjfv8E=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNpr2rLGxolNgDkH3XHAxUCPeS_13jHK1QEFyIQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNrYruIqjglCD3Rum9osjB70uWrEShhoYPJ_gAG=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMdqqBuTNYp89O5BzWzRT7BotDiTSkT_1NyjzlD=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPY5SR4fOrZEZIQgdgeVDGvAZJrRPSp3vu1RWCZ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPb0bRifE-o6jqfeh_im5f0OE-y1lDMlrrdKzSl=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPQ1JGVdztUdWZtX0tcvSvp2B6gVXvKbb2Nf64d=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures><resp>None</resp><gmapID>0x808506614c768671:0xde51b62058db3bce</gmapID></record></dataset><record>

< review>
Was so excited to celebrate an anniversary here. First off, I understand it's COVID. I know restaurants are under unimaginable pressure with all of the public health regulations. This place took it too far. I was scolded the whole night! My drink took forever which normally I wouldn't mind but I knew once it hit the table the policing would stop. I've been dining out for months since things have opened up and I've never had so much nannying once I've already been sat at a table. We didn't experience this at any other restaurants in the Valley that weekend or the weekend prior.

We would have left but it was late and they had our CC charged for the res. If the food was great it would have softened the blow to this terrible experience but it was lackluster. The tempura was soft. Tempura without a bite is a tragedy. The fish was slimy and flavorless. Our favorite part of the meal was the bread! Sourdough whole wheat? The patio is gorgeous with the awning and soft light. They did nail the ambiance.<//review>

< text>
The food was amazing!  The service was friendly and I didn't feel a pompous attitude from anybody in the staff.

I spent Valentine's evening dinner here and they really made the night special.  It was 5 course prix fixe menu that offered a wine pairing with 4 of the 5 dishes.  The 5th and final dish was dessert and for an additional charge of $15 for that pairing.

Overall the cost breakdown was as follows:
$150 5-course prix fixe menu
$80 for 4 wine pairings
$15 additional wine pairing with dessert
20% Service charge (no additional tip required)

I'm not one to dine at fine dining establishments often, but I felt as if the service was amazing.  Our main server was fun and friendly.  She was attentive to our pacing.  Each dish we had came paired with some wine.  As we finished each course, we always had some wine leftover in our glasses.  She ensured we had time to finish our wine prior to bringing out the next course.  Because of her, we didn't feel rushed.  We had time to enjoy our wine and have good conversations without feeling rushed.

Given the cost, everything was completely worth it.  It's not a place an average person can afford, but it was definitely an experience worth having at least once in your life.< /text>

<text>Underwhelming!

We recently¬†spent a long weekend in Yountville for a special occasion but unfortunately, no aspect of our experience at La Toque met our expectations. After being greeted warmly and being offered a glass of champagne to start off, we both picked our tasting menus. One of the reasons we chose La Toque was that they do offer a vegetable tasting menu, which my fianc√© chose. Unfortunately, her dinner was a big disappointment all around. The bottom line was that there was just not enough food and whatever was there was not very special at all. The cauliflower soup to start was probably the best course. The tempura vegetables were dry and fried too long, the wild mushrooms were barely a taste, and there was even less of the heirloom beets. At that point she really hoped for the pasta, but what arrived were two small specks of noodle, a few green dots, one sunchoke and maybe a mushroom (we‚Äôre not sure). All around, her dinner was a complete bust and she walked out of the restaurant hungry.

I chose the standard tasting menu and didn‚Äôt fare much better. Most courses on the standard tasting menu were just not that special. The greeting from the kitchen ‚Äì deviled duck eggs ‚Äì were tasty. My choices after that were carpaccio (bland), black cod (the fish was fine, the accompanying sauce was the best part of my dinner), duck breast (not a lot of meat, tender but hardly any sides), and then red snapper (odd to have fish after duck again ‚Äì the fermented beans were weird and the rest of the sides were not exciting). Our desserts ‚Äì the wall of chocolate and the truffle ice cream sandwich ‚Äì were also just OK and plain and simple not good enough to convince us that we had just eaten dinner at a Michelin starred restaurant.

Aside from the disappointing food, one of the other things that we did not like was the fact that eating at La Toque felt like you had a fine dining dinner at a hotel restaurant that will serve a buffet breakfast at the same place a few hours later. Tables were set with odd fitted plastic covers that do not at all convey a feeling of high-end dining and tables, chairs and booths placed in a non-descript square room felt cheap.

Unfortunately, this was not at all what we hoped for. We do not recommend La Toque.< /text>< Pictures>

<UserId.>115004331187763089633< /UserId.>< name>
Christopher Tegtmeyer</name>
< date>
1572226621576< /date>
<Rate>2< /Rate>< Review>
After enjoying multiple Michelin starred restaurants throughout Europe, we were very underwhelmed by La Toque.  To start, we were seated in a booth after the staff never even offered to take our jackets.  The booth was along a window that faced the hotel entry driveway which flashed headlights directly at us until we finally closed the drapes on our own.  The ambiance was further ruined by overly bright fake candles on the table and music that was distractingly loud.  The food overall, especially on the vegetarian tasting menu, was uninspired and lacked flavor.  It was disappointing to have an entire course composed of only half an avocado still in the skin with a small amount of tomato broth.  Multiple courses had mushrooms not cut properly leaving the unpleasant, woody root at the bottom.  The best dish was what the staff brought to compensate for the dry and utterly flavorless  vegetarian cassoulet.  Lastly, while the sommelier was clearly very knowledge and paired the wines well with the food, he lacked passion in his interaction with us and seemed to simply recite a preset script. Overall, I question how this establishment has maintained a Michelin star.</Review>

< Text>
I only gave this four stars so as not to affect the score for this restaurant. However, to give the restaurant the sense of the power of bad google reviews let me relay the following -- after making reservations at La Toque, I decided I'd rather eat the $100 than risk what seems like a terrible service experience after reading the reviews here the day before we were supposed to dine.  If you read the reviews, several them note slow, poor service.  The owner or someone working for them attempts to make excuses, but when you have that many folks making the same comments, they can't all be wrong.  If this were not Michelin starred or didn't cost a high amount, you could forgive some of it.  But service is one of the key points to a Michelin restaurant and I hope the guide takes note of it in the future.  It doesn't help that there's very mixed reviews about this place as well when you ask people who actually live here and reiterate the service issues.  Service and quality servers are within the control of the restaurant.  Look at other Michelin starred places -- I don't think I've ever seen such comments at other restaurants in such volume.  We skipped and had a fine meal elsewhere.  The reviews are read by fine diners and this particular diner took the warnings from others here seriously.<//Text>
</record>

<userid>105584068529383532299<//userid><user_name>Honey Jayne< /user_name>< Date>
1575406152692<//Date>
<Rating>5< /Rating><text>I have enjoyed many meals at La Toque, and each one has kept me coming back for more.  Extremely talented chefs with knowledgeable servers & sommeliers.  They do fun things throughout the meal that remind me why they have held their Michelin star for so many many years.

Chefs menu let's you enjoy the best of what La Toque offers without having to make any decisions.  Traditionally, you get 9 courses that includes appetizers, mids, mains, cheese & desserts.

There are also 4 & 5 courses options where you get to create your own dining experience by selecting 3-4 savory dishes plus a dessert or cheese to finish things off.

Last but definitely not least, La Toque offers a full vegetarian tasting menu!  Get the 7 course veggie tasting as a full menu, or choose dishes from it to incorporate into your 4-5 course choices.

Adding the optional wine pairings for any of the pre-fixed menus is a sure fire way to take this meal to the next level because La Toque holds Wine Spectator's highest award for excellence.

Truly something for everyone!  If you find yourself lucky enough to be dinning when it is Truffle season, you can enjoy their amazing truffle sandwich or even a full truffle Chefs tasting menu.  Chef Ken Frank has an amazing way with both black & white truffles!

Each dining experience takes about 2-4 hours depending on how many courses & how fast you eat.  I highly recommend making reservations, but they do accept walk-ins as well. Valet Parking is validated by the restaurant, there is a coat check and a full bar available.  You can also eat at a special table in the kitchen, where the magic happens, at the chef's table.<//text>< Pics>
None</Pics>
< response>
None< /response>

<Review>I would have given La Toque 1/4 of a star if that was possible.  Their website boasts Michelin star cuisine but their service is far from a Michelin star.  I recently celebrated my birthday dinner at La Toque and my wife and I enjoyed their tasting menu, paired with a variety of wines.  The food and wine was fantastic.  After receiving the check, our server accidentally spilled the remaining wine from my wife's glass all over her white dress.  We did not make a fuss in order to avoid the server getting into trouble.  The manager came over and told us she would pay for our dry cleaning and gave us her card.  When we told her we are from out of town, she just said, "you can send the bill from anywhere in the country and I will take care of it."  When I asked the manager if she felt dry cleaning was an acceptable way to resolve an unfortunate birthday and dining experience, she replied, "I heard you spilled the wine on your wife...I am going on the information I was told."  I would expect this response from the counter supervisor at a fast food joint, not from a manager representing a Michelin star restaurant.  Would I recommend this restaurant to anyone looking for a fine dining experience?  No.  However, I would suggest the management of La Toque require their entire team undergo some basic training in service and hospitality.  You cannot advertise to serve Michelin star food if your service is as good or less than what you get at the local drive thru.<//Review>< name>
Peter Wehbe</name>

< Text>
We went to La Toque, as I had such a great experience there 6 years ago. Michelin star restaurant, known for it's wine parings. We ordered the 5 course meal, and chose our courses. The Chef's table was below the counter level of the kitchen so we couldn't see anything except the dirty dish parade from the dining room to the dishwasher. The decor was two brown plastic place mats. the food was just ounces per serving, the wines were unknown and unremarkable short pours, there was not even garnish on some of the dishes, the service was average, and the bill was over the top and accompanied by a 20% service charge, just under $300.00!!!</Text>

<review>This is my first Michelin star experience. First of all, the plates are really tiny, as people were talking about. Each dish is meticulously prepared, and the presentation is nice. La Toque offers a 9 course chef recommended dinner, or a 4 to 5 course build your own type of dinner. The 9 course easily runs you about $250 per person (with wine). I had the 4 course dinner. I ordered a Cappacio (raw beef), duck breast, rib eye steak and a chocolate dessert. I would say the steak is the best, the duck and raw beef was OK. The service was nice, very attentive and polite. There are about 3 people serving us for the night. The total comes to about $250 for 2. Is the food amazing? Probably not. I have had better duck, beef and steak elsewhere. You are mostly paying for the experience.<//review>< pics>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
Happened to find this place on a short trip to Napa Valley and loved it.  The atmosphere is relaxing and offers an upscale feel without feeling over formal, the staff were attentive, and the food was easily worth the price.  We were almost put off by the offer of only a chef's menu but there are sufficient and varied choices at each level to guarantee everyone will be able to find something they really like.  We happened to find the four course perfect for the two of us.  We are not dessert people but it would have been a shame to miss that course.  And it is so nice to experience fine dining in a an establishment where you can readily hold a conversation because you can hear.   A perfect end to that part of our trip.</Text>

Not worthy of a Michelin Star.  We had the worst experience at La Toque.  Went to celebrate our engagement and ordered a multi-course meal with wine pairing.  Without asking permission, the restaurant decided to replace a duplicate wine pairing with Champagne- which doesn't agree with my fiance.  When we noticed the Champagne we asked for it to be replaced with another wine.  The Sommelier, in the most unprofessional, rude and condescending tone said "Oh, I guess you didn't notice the champagne glass on the table before I poured it."  This nastiness and pettiness from the Sommelier was SHOCKING- for any service experience let alone a $600 meal.  We told the manager on duty and they replaced the Sommelier for the remaining course; however, our experience was already ruined.  We were given a bottle of wine to try to mitigate for the experience - which living 3,000 miles away doesn't really mean anything to us because we can't travel with the wine.  Two days later, after reflecting on how poor our experience was, we went back to the restaurant to speak with the General Manager.  He could have not been more rude.  Did not apologize.  Told us the issue was "handled."  And then TOOK THE BOTTLE OF WINE BACK and walked away!

We both thought the food was delicious; however, service is a key factor to a fine dining experience and it does not matter how delicious the food is when the service was so abysmal.  Shame on you La Toque for ruining our entire experience.

I hope this restaurant loses it's Michelin star.  They are not worthy of the designation.  It's bad enough to have a one-off bad experience with a Sommelier but the follow-up by management was even more rude and more upsetting.

The owner's response is to recklessly and maliciously call us "bullies" and "jerks." How about owning up to your staff verbally abusing a guest? And perhaps you should look through the aggregate of your reviews on Google, Trip Advisor, Yelp and Facebook because many other guests share my view of your service.< /text>

< Review>
VERY disappointing!  This place is located in the Westin Resort in Napa--and looks the part (exactly like a hotel restaurant).

Service was slow--we had to wait unacceptably long periods (several times) while our server seemed to not know we were waiting for our next course, even though the sommelier had already poured our next wine pairing. When asked, she seemed annoyed.

We are not "newbies" to fine cuisine and excellent service: while the food was good, it was not of the outstanding level we expected at a "Michelin Star" restaurant in the Napa Valley.

The bill included a 20% service charge-- I was unable to identify anything about the service that was worth some $160 alone--the service was no better (and no more labor intensive) than I would receive at ANY restaurant.  Why should expensive food automatically result in a larger tip for the server, anyway?

Update:  see management's response-- it's all our fault? Even McDonald's knows "the customer is always right"...  this attitude is why the service was so poor....< /Review>
<user_id>113083143407860844522</user_id>< Response>
{'time': 1540165952746, 'text': "I am so sorry you were disappointed with your experience here at La Toque.  You ordered our Chef's Table Tasting Menu.  This menu is 11 courses long (with amuses) and we typically allow 3 to 4 hours for dining at a relaxed pace.  The menu is designed to be savored and enjoyed over that period of time.\nYou stated that you waited for long periods of time between courses.  Your reservation was at 7:00 and when you informed us partway through your meal that you needed to be finished by 9:00 because you had a car waiting, we did our best to move things along at speed.  Your main courses were on the table at 8:50, less than two hours after you began your meal.\nYou mention that the sommelier had poured your wine and you had to wait for the next course.  That is the typical order for service.  We pour the wine first, then the food is served.  There are pauses between the two.\nLastly, you stated that you paid $160.00 in a service charge.  This, like the rest of your claims, is inflated.  The service charge for your dinner that evening was $134.00.  You asked why expensive food should result in a larger tip?  It based on percentages. We add a 20% service charge to all menus.  That percentage is pretty standard for a high-end restaurant. All of that money does not go to the waiter alone.  Our service charge goes to all of the staff on the floor front waiters, back waiters, sommeliers and it is shared by the kitchen as well.  All service charges are pooled.\nIn the future, to avoid being disappointed with the pacing of your dinner, you should inform the host or your waiter that you have a timeline that you need to stick to.  They can then help steer you to the appropriate dining experience."}<//Response>

< time>
1333650018272< /time>
<rate>5</rate><Text>Apparently known as the mini French Laundry La toque is certainly in the same class, except the portions are American French not French. The food is excellent and the service is almost completely impeccable with very minor and occasional infractions: I noticed 2 approaches from the wrong side and an asynchronous dish delivery in a party of four diners eating four courses each. The red meat was prepared exactly properly, of fine cuts, including a mild lamb and tender antelope, with the carpaccio being notably exceptional in a fantastic group. The sea food dishes: Lobster linguini - very good-, the squid ink  scallop -masterful- , and himachi -excellent- were all of exceptional quality fish. The Sommelier was able to formulate a rare and novel, but very excellent cocktail on request to vague taste guidelines, and offer helpful suggestions to wine taste requests to fit within the half bottle list as well as curb side education on up and coming wine regions. I am constantly disappointed by Sommelier service but was very pleased here by the red headed female Sommelier whose name I regretfully cannot recall. I would certainly revisit La toque and rank it easily in my top ten fine dining experiences at #3.< /Text></record>

< rate>

<userid>112402214680656830849</userid><Pics>None</Pics>< text>
Delicious pizza and suds! We beat the Sunday crowd by getting there at 5pm. It was busy by 6pm, but the food came out quick enough for us, but appetizers helped. There's a food only line on the right. Food and brew line to the left. Ask for samples of their brews.
Pizza was nice and doughy, but not thick like pan pizza, not too thin either. Loads of toppings!!!
The Carlsbad was outstanding... hope you like artichoke, pesto and fetaüòâ. BBQ cheeseburger had meatballs, not ground beef, I liked it more than I thought I would. I was expecting weird, but the meatballs made it seem more traditional.
Wings were baked, not bready. (The way i like it)
We got the veggie basket as a side, it was ideal for a family of 4 or two really hungry people.
For you beer bodies, they offer cans, growlers, and 6 packs to go.
There's a small parking lot adjacent and there's a pay to park across the street. If you want free parking, plan on street parking and walking a block or two.</text>

<text>Killer pizza! This place does not disappoint. Dropped in with a group of college friends who were staying in Ocean Beach.

Pizza Port has a very chilled, laid-back vibe. We were quickly able to find a long table that accommodated our group. Note, that the tables are shared, so don't be afraid to chat up your neighbor.

Pizza took about 35 mins to bake, and we enjoyed few rounds of beer while waiting, along with the jalapeno poppers (highly recommend!). We tried the Garlic Veggie Pizza w/ traditional crust. Super fresh veggies and gooey cheese.

We will defiantly be back on our next trip to SD!</text>< pics>

<GmapID>0x80deaa3a261cd2e3:0x3e89464c53bf352< /GmapID><Text>I have been a fan of Pizza Port for many years. They keep the menu simple with pizza, salad, breadsticks, mozzarella sticks, and buffalo chicken wings and craft beer and soda and iced tea. I love all their food and they have lunch specials, like two slices and a drink or a slice, salad, and a beverage (non-alcoholic), and a couple other options. You can substitute a beer for an additional charge. They have the proper social distancing protocols on keeping your mask on when you are not seated at your table. You have to ask for napkins, utensils, parmesan cheese, or red pepper flakes.
The service is friendly and helpful. I fully recommend this Pizza Port in Ocean Beach, San Diego.
The toughest part about the Ocean Beach (OB) location is parking is scarce. Especially with the social distancing protocols in place, they took over the small 7 parking spot lot for outdoor dining.</Text>< user>

----------------Editted a few months later-----------------

Edit: From five to three stars for super rude staff. First I tried to order slices and the bartender told me they weren't doing slices so I ordered two small pizzas. Before my order came up I watched several people order and pick up individual slices. So I then had two small pizzas and needed some to-go boxes. They normally have them sitting out to help yourself. They didn't have any available so I requested two boxes from the staff. The busser said to me "two boxes? Why do you need two boxes?" I explained I had two pizzas but he retorted with "uh huh." I allowed my -well over 21- boyfriend to sample my beer (he didn't want one but wanted to try it) and we had the busser inform us that he couldn't taste my drink without getting ID'ed by the bartender and then said if he saw it again he would "have to bounce us". Asking for an ID would have sufficed. He absolutely did not need to treat us like we were breaking the law. This is a brewery, you have to assume people will sample each other's drinks. It's not accepted to threaten to remove someone from the property over it without requesting an ID first.

I don't know if they were recently hit with a fine or what but this behavior is a little wild. This place has been a favorite of ours for years and the entire atmosphere totally flipped. I hope that this trend doesn't continue because it makes it extremely uncomfortable to dine and relax.<//Review><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNgqr1ia3e42xe7M-kDoUDFu_sVOVGjHsS6rf0i=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics>< Response>

<Time>1528700948747</Time><resp>None<//resp><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNfrX949lJWoaprOxcwitwpuLNv859ZUvAvRiWj=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><Text>Pizza Port's OB location is a staple for every one of my visits to the area. It captures the spirit of the area so well - surf, beer, and a loose and casual feel. Just a little off the main drag, it's within easy reach for tired surfers and rubbernecks alike, and makes a fine choice when Hodad's is running a line around the corner.

First, I've really only had the pizza. And it's good, competing with NY Slice style pizza around San Diego (East Coasters might turn their nose up at the place, FWIW.) I've also sampled the kale salad which was inappropriately healthy given the settings. The real treat here is the beer, which is always diverse, experimental, affordable, and delicious. Pizza Port's social media game has been overshadowed by newer players, but the brewing and taste is still on point, and matches supremely with the pizza available.

Head in during the lunch special and get away with two slices and a beer for less than $10, then get back to the beach with your newly acquired gut. Or return to the main street and go shopping, if you can resist the temptation to nap.<//Text><Rating>5< /Rating><gmap_id>0x80deaa3a261cd2e3:0x3e89464c53bf352<//gmap_id><username>Garrett Bredell<//username></record>

<user>107422422651875999620</user><user_name>Shone Bowman</user_name>< date>

< Rate>
2</Rate>
< text>
WARNING: Do NOT place orders via ChowNow.

I've been a regular at the OB and Solana Beach Pizza Port locations since childhood.

Yesterday, I placed an order online for pickup at the OB Pizza Port via ChowNow.  I arrived 15 minutes after receiving the notification that the food was ready.  Due to an error between the shop and ChowNow, my order was never received so I waited for it to be prepared (outside, standing on the curb due to COVID restrictions) after being quoted 15 minutes.  30 minutes later, I checked on the progress and was informed that I had been made the incorrect pizza and that they would finish the one I ordered in 10 minutes.  One hour after I initially arrived to pick up my food, I finally received what I ordered.

The women who served me were very kind and offered the incorrectly-made pizza for free in addition to what I ordered, which I really appreciated.  Unfortunately, because I had to wait an hour to receive my order, my girlfriend missed a seminar she needed to attend.  Going forward, I unfortunately won't be providing my business to the OB location.<//text>

<GmapID>0x80deaa3a261cd2e3:0x3e89464c53bf352<//GmapID>< Rating>
3</Rating>
<resp>None<//resp><Time>1576568340199</Time><review>It was okay. I was disappointed because I took my kids here SPECIFICALLY to have some of their house-made root beer and when I ordered it, was told that the machine was broken. Oddly enough, that was the same story I got when I visited the Solana Beach location a couple of years ago. Regardless, if they're not going to offer an item, I think that the menu board should note that it's not available. Also, I ordered the lunch special and when I told the clerk what type of pizza I wanted, she replied that the only options were cheese, pepperoni, or the pizza of the day. The menu board says "any slice pizza" - again, if it's only certain types of pizza that are available with the special, then the menu should note that, not say "Any." I ordered the pizza of the day and it was yummy. It was hot and fresh, and the servings were large. The orders came out in a reasonable amount of time. If you're not a regular, it's a little unclear what you're supposed to do after you're finished eating - bus your own table? Leave it there? Some signage would help with that too. All in all, it was an ok experience. I wouldn't drive out of my way to go there again (like I did this time) and circle the block again & again looking for parking, but if I was already in the area, I'd eat there.</review></record>

<pictures>None< /pictures><review>Fantastic, absolutely fantastic! So many delicious pizza options and a beer menu that goes on for days, what more could you ask for?

Went here for the first time for dinner with a group of co-workers. Ordered the Pizza Lahaina, Pizza Laguna, and Pizza San Clemente (love the pizzas named after California beaches). Each pizza was more scrumptious than the next! I never would have believed that a pizza with black bean sauce as its base could be so good but it was a revelation. My favorite was the Lahaina, but I'm one of those people who likes pineapple on a pizza with Canadian bacon.

Great, laid-back atmosphere at this place. The next time I'm in San Diego, Pizza Port will be on the short-list of places to go!< /review>< Time>

< Text>
Great for a crowd. Went for a birthday party with a group of six. We ordered individually and ordered too much food. Medium pies are quite large. They offer many different preset pizza options along with a create your own. We had the Mac and Cheese bites to start and they were good. Lots of video games and entertainment for the kids. Also a craft brewery on the premise. Very laid back experience. Order at the window and they call out your name to pick up the order. The announcer took some liberties with his announcements and created some smiles. Would go back with a crowd. Would not go by myself.< /Text>

<user_id>116753486321307298684</user_id>< Text>
I love their "wings" night on thursday's!  At 49 cents each it's a good deal, but it's only for "Dine In"  I would go early because it gets very busy and very crowded.  They are a very popular spot!  They're wings are great (though I've only tried a few different ones.)  I love their pizzas and the selection.  They can come up with some unusual combinations, but they're fun to try!  I hear (through people I go with and family members) that their beers are fantastic!  Great selection and reasonably priced.  I would recommend Pizza Port, but if you don't like crowds go on a week night (Monday or Tuesday) or during the week before 6pm.<//Text>

<UserId.>108766632033484052865< /UserId.><Name>Jessica Nettles<//Name>< time>
1561488796531</time>
<Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
Once again, while looking for pizza we found this place and just the pictures of the food alone brought us into Pizza Port on a Saturday afternoon.  We came with our 3 children, and while I wouldn't necessarily call it a "family restaurant" I was comfortable with my two youngest being there because it's a loud, upbeat place where their noise levels would bother no one.
It took a few minutes to decide what we wanted, but we had an order of buffalo wings, which were dry rub and not super saucy, so they were good.  My littlest two each had slices of their favorite pizzas and the hubby and I each got a small, he had the San Clemente, and I the margherita pizza.  The individual slices were insane, they were bigger than the plates they were on.  The San Clemente has a black bean sauce, and it had this unique flavor that made me think I was eating somewhere between a taco and a pizza...it was quite good.  Then of course there was the Margherita pizza.  Not the best one I have ever had, but it was good and I would eat it again.   Truth be told though, I tasted the San Clemente first and it was so flavorful and yummy that maybe my tastebuds were a little screwy and the Margherita was just plain at that point.
We also enjoyed a Beer Float, something we'd discussed trying many many times, but had never actually come across.  We did at Pizza Port, and the options for beers in my float were amazing.  I went with a coffee porter and was pleasantly surprised.  Not gonna lie, I was skeptical, but I came out of this experience a fan.
This location is good for an afternoon slice and a cold beer or two.  Bringing the kids is totally fine, and going without them is totally fine too.
The atmosphere is laid back, the food is good, and the beer is cold.  What more could you ask for?</Review>

< Review>
Pizza Port is always poppin'. I drove by it 100s of times while living in Cardiff by the Sea. It's packed at lunch and dinner. They make their own beer there too. Try the honey beer. It's full of awesomeness.

It's kid friendly and has video game arcades too. The only thing I didn't like too much about it is the lack of seating available, but I guess that's what happens when you get great pizza and beer.

You basically order your pizza at the register and find a seat as fast as someone stands up. They will call your name over the loud speaker. No waiters here. Lots of fun. There is also another location (i think in Ocean Beach).<//Review>

< Text>
Great spot but be prepared for a crowd and lots of kids.  The tables are pretty close together and it was a little difficult for me to transfer from my wheelchair to a bench seat but thats not the restaurants fault, it's the fault of the able-bodied family sitting at the only handicap accessible table. The employees are friendly and the pizza was stupid good. Great spot for a slice or a whole pie if you are in a group.  They do have a gluten free option for the crust but it's $3 more for those of you in need a GF option.  Plus they were advertising for a hemp beer that is brewed with hemp seeds, on the table that I think I will have to try out next time.</Text>

<user_name>Douglas LeClair< /user_name><Resp>None<//Resp><gmapID>0x80deaa3a261cd2e3:0x3e89464c53bf352<//gmapID><date>1412382964574</date><text>I give Pizza Port 5 stars for the beer and 4 stars for the food. However I have a lot of non-craft beer drinking friends that come here just for the food, so my standards might be high. To me the pizza is the perfect complement to their beer - doughy, cheesy and loaded with toppings. Their beers are very underrated compared to other breweries in San Diego, mostly because they make so many that aren't all world-class. But all of them are above average, priced fairly, and served fresh from the brewery in a casual family-friendly environment. Frequently Pizza Port creates some beers that really knock it out of the park (Santa's Little Helper, Mongo IPA, Bacon & Eggs Breakfast Coffee Porter, etc.) They have a generous amount of taps devoted to "guest brewery beers" including Russian River, Ballast Point, etc. Their homemade root beer is awesome, I recommend trying a float. Or try some of their "beer buddies" which is cooked pizza dough bites brushed with garlic butter.< /text>< UserId.>

<Name>Ian - Fr0wnZ< /Name>< user_id>
113897371292918169007<//user_id>
< text>
Came in with a group of friends for our last meal during our San Diego trip. Most of the group heard great things about Pizza Port, so it had to be a clear winner? Parking can be an issue with limited spots available, but luckily we found street parking about a block away.

The atmosphere of the restaurant looked fun and inviting. There were many flat screen TV's around the restaurant playing the football game. The seating reminded me of long park bench tables, big enough to fit large parties of 20 or 30. The craft beer bar is located on the left side of the restaurant while food is in the middle.

As far as food, Pizza Port offers premium gourmet pizzas. I originally wanted the Pizza SF but two friends had already ordered that, so I just randomly chose the featured month pizza, Teriyaki Chicken. It was just okay and I probably wouldn't get it again. The flavors didn't mesh well for me; carrots & broccoli inside a cheesy pizza. The pizza's are portioned generously, so if you're one person just go with the individual. There's also arcade games towards the back of the pizza restaurant. Pizza Port reminds me of an adult Shakey's. I will definitely come back but order the pizza I want regardless of who in the group gets it.</text>
</record>
</dataset><record>

< Text>
Don‚Äôt be fooled by the name, Pizza Port is a great pizza place as well, but even if they didn‚Äôt have pizza at all, they would be a pretty great bar and brewery. The outside patio section under some palm trees is awesome on nice days. The inside is huge with lots of long tables and great for big gatherings or small get togethers alike. The beer menu is huge as the Pizza Port brewing empire has several facilities. There are probably close to 3 dozen beers on tap across the range from blonde ales to porters. There are of course multiple hop forward IPAs that go great on a hot day. Even the malty wheat and ales are pretty delicious. The inside is a good place to catch sports as well with many TVs. The pizza isn‚Äôt bad either. This is your place to go to grab a pint after some time in the sun on the beach for sure.< /Text>

<Rating>4<//Rating><review>This is the quintessential surfer/craft beer hangout.  I think I literally saw Jeff Spicoli (if you're not old enough to know who that is, forget it).

On a serious note, the only thing that is not awesome about this place is the parking situation, but then again what can you expect in OB and thank the flying spaghetti monster that there are no soul sucking multi-story parking garages ruining the vibe that is OB.

I haven't been to the other Pizza Ports yet, but this one was fantastic albeit packed to the gills.  As you probably already know there is a plethora of home brewed craft beers, as well as plenty of guest taps.  Heavy on the D/I/PAs, in fact when I was there I think they had 7 IPAs and  3 or 4 DIPAs.  The beer line and the pizza line are separate and there are virtually no vegetarian pizza options, unless you roll your own (which you can if you want).

If I lived in OB (I'm not sure how this is possible anymore with real estate prices the way they are) I'd be there several times a week.<//review><pictures>None</pictures><Resp>None<//Resp>< gmapID>

<Name>Lyndsi Winer<//Name><resp>None</resp><date>1409024064431< /date><Text>I can't particularly say I LOVE their pizza but it's ok.  Their atmosphere is great and their beer even better. They brew their own beer and dozens of types!  All SUPER SUPER awesome!  It's a place for craft beer aficionados!  Their staff is always happy to be there and happy to serve you and I very rarely can complain about them.  The pizza is ok, they have great specialty ingredients and the larger the pizza the better the crust I think.  Don't get a small if you don't like a lot of dough more like a hand tossed pan pizza.  The large is good and the lunch slices even better!  In fact they have the best lunch deal in town!  An amazing garden salad that me and my bf share and HUGE slices of pizza and soda for 5$ and if you want a beer its a 1$ more for regular beer and 2$ for stronger beers.  They always have a unique slice of the day accompanied with the choice also of pepperoni or cheese everyday and the slice with the salad is perfect!  I ate this almost daily when I worked across the street!  They are fast and the lunch is good and soooooo cheap!! They also have great salads!  The port salad is one of my favs!  It's all veggies and has so much in it that is unique you'll never miss the meat!  Roasted red peppers, blue cheese, spring mix, marinated portobellos and more!  It's to die for!!!<//Text>< gmapID>

<userid>100509411568229826459<//userid>< user_name>
Ezzy Crisan<//user_name>
< date>
1411330982366< /date>
< Rate>
4</Rate>
< Review>
We came here to hang out with friends, and this was a perfect spot. Great food, great beer selections, and great company!

We came here on a Sunday night, a night before Memorial day. It's been awhile, and I completely forgot how crazy busy it is in these Ocean Beach streets. We got luckily how easily we found a table fit for 8 people.  The place is always packed and  loud, however people are quite polite and respectful.

We tried out the honey beers, Carlsbad pizza, cajun bites, garlic bites and chicken wings.  The honey beers were a treat for me. I'm not much of a beer drinker, but the Honey beer is something I would keep ordering. It's light, tart, and a hint of honey for the after taste.  The carlsbad pizza intrigued me --with the mix of artichoke hearts, feta cheese, alfredo sauce and peppers. The pizza was a tasty creation. The saltiness and sweetness flavors worked well with the ingredients. Though, the chicken wings didn't impress me much. It was average. The cajun & garlic bites were ok. They were made in a pizza bread, and then cut into pieces, cajun ---with jalapenos & garlic -- stating the obvious, and put into a basket to share.

Whenever I'm in Ocean Beach, I'd be back here for the assortment of beers and pizza selections!</Review>
